    "reasoning": "The requirement is to implement a single stage of an n-bit shift register. The inputs are: w (data from the previous stage), R (data to load), E (enable shift), and L (load signal). The output is Q. \n\nLogic Analysis:\n1. Load Operation: If L is asserted, the output Q should take the value of R. This is a synchronous load operation.\n2. Shift Operation: If L is not asserted, but E is asserted, the output Q should take the value of the previous stage's input, which is w.\n3. Hold Operation: If neither L nor E is asserted, the current value of Q should be maintained.\n\nPriority: Usually, in shift registers, the 'Load' signal has higher priority than the 'Shift' signal. If L is high, we load R. If L is low and E is high, we shift in w. Otherwise, we hold.\n\nImplementation Steps:\n- Declare the output Q as a logic register.\n- Use an `always @(posedge clk)` block to implement the sequential logic.\n- Use an `if-else` structure inside the block: `if (L) Q <= R; else if (E) Q <= w; else Q <= Q;` (or simply omit the else to hold).\n- Initialize Q to 0 using an `initial` block to avoid unknown states at startup, as per instructions.\n\nAdvice to avoid syntax errors:\n- Ensure all ports are declared with correct types (logic).\n- Ensure the module name matches the specification (TopModule).\n- Use non-blocking assignments (`<=`) for sequential logic.\n- Do not use `always @(posedge clk or posedge reset)` unless a reset signal is actually provided in the interface; here, there is no reset signal, so we use an `initial` block for initialization.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic w,\n    input  logic R,\n    input  logic E,\n    input  logic L,\n    output logic Q\n);\n\n    // Initialize Q to a known value to avoid X at start of simulation\n    initial begin\n        Q = 1'b0;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic for shift register stage\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (L) begin\n            // Load operation (highest priority)\n            Q <= R;\n        end else if (E) begin\n            // Shift operation\n            Q <= w;\n        end\n        // If neither L nor E is asserted, Q holds its value implicitly\n    end\n\nendmodule"
